node.text: Eileen Mockus, CEO of sustainable homeware company @Coyuchi, talks with @archdigestpro editor @katy_magic about how to make your home more sustainable by making a few simple design choices.

node.title: In Conversation: Eileen Mockus, CEO of @coyuchi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 08, 2021. May be an image of furniture and kitchen.

node.text:
For architect @vincentvanduysen, working on @jennikayne's L.A. home afforded a welcome opportunity to explore the intersection of his own highly distilled, Belgian-born architectural language with the lingua franca of an entirely different culture and climate. “I’m a modernist, heart and soul, and I’ve always been inspired by the particular kind of modernism that emerged in California. I was interested to see how I could participate in that history and still remain true to my own work,” the architect explains, characterizing Kayne’s home as a “beautiful synchronization of a midcentury attitude revisited by a Belgian attitude.”

Tour more of the home at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; architecture by @vincentvanduysen and @humbertonobrega; design by @jennikaynehome; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 08, 2021. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
Even totally empty and, by all accounts, a bit of a mess, the Paris apartment of fashion designer @pierrehardy and husband @christopherturnier was bursting with life—elaborate mythological frescoes covered almost every inch of its soaring, nearly 15-foot ceilings. Apollo, robed in crimson, harp in hand, looked down upon the entrance hall. In the living room, Juno, wife of Jupiter, and Aeolus, Greek god of wind, lounged in the clouds, while Aurora, Roman goddess of dawn—resplendent amid a magnificent medley of cherubs and horses—presided over another room. The masterworks, attributed to the artist Bon Boullogne, best known for his easel paintings found at Versailles and the Louvre, were a serious selling point.

Explore their elegant apartment at our bio link. Photo by @francoishalard; design by @vdecotiis; words by @_h_mart_.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 07, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
Maximizing natural light and modernizing the once octagonal floor plan were just two of the goals designer @arielokin had when it came to the renovation of an apartment on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan. Hired by a couple who wished to preserve the bones of the beautiful pre-war-era home overlooking Central Park, Ariel aimed to maintain as much original detailing, like the beveled glass pocket doors, while reimagining the layout, adding sleek fixtures, plus an array of art and midcentury furnishings. The result? A layered, serene space with pops of bold color.

Go behind the design – and read more from @getclever – at our bio link. Photo by @donnadotanphoto; design by @arielokin; words by Lauren Jones.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 07, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
In this mountainside home in Big Sky, Montana, designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) used Venetian plaster and wall coverings to imbue the home with more warmth than paint alone could provide. A @kravetinc fabric seen in the boys’ bedroom, and textured wallpapers, such as one @phillipjeffriesltd selection, proved to be particularly exemplary selections.

Tour the entire home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by @ericrallen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 07, 2021.

node.text:
“Instead of drywall and paint, we try to use natural materials and finishes to establish the color palette and the mood,” notes @woods_dangaran partner Joseph Dangaran, emphasizing the warmth of this L.A. home's composition. Natural illumination from a skylight animates the primary bath. The architects honed the Patagonia marble to minimize the stone’s reflectivity.

Tour the beautiful spaces at our bio link. Photo by @joefletcherphoto; design by @woods_dangaran; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 06, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“I told [@jobsmeets] we would give him carte blanche,” says @viktorandrolf designer Rolf Snoeren about his wild and whacky Amsterdam home, though he admits to having had second thoughts. The two designers can be equally stubborn, “so maybe it might not have been a good idea,” he gingerly allows. “Creating crazy and stunning is easy for him, but creating warmth, which [Brandon O'Dell] wanted, is a bit more of a challenge.”

See how Smeets pulled it off at our bio link. Photo by @kasiagatkowskaphotography; design by @jobsmeets; styled by @_barbaraberends_; words by @mrmitchowens.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 06, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Often, friends make the best collaborators. So for Australian model and Luma Beauty founder Jessica Hart (@jesshart) and seasoned interiors editor, stylist, and designer Carlos Mota (@casamotachic), a decorating partnership was a long time coming. “I’ve just always really admired Carlos’s taste and love for all things colorful and amazing,” says Hart. And when Mota caught wind that she was giving up her glamorous Gramercy Park apartment for a Spanish-style house in the Hollywood Hills, he immediately offered up his services. “I said, ‘When you move to L.A., I would love to help,’ ” Mota recalls.

Tour her home from our September issue at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @casamotachic; words by @carly_olson.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 06, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
In 2019, the Seattle-based founder of Brian Paquette Interiors (@brian.paquette_) and his husband, Justin, braved a blizzard to see a recently listed property just six blocks away from the townhouse where they lived. That effort turned out to be well worth the snowy trek, as the house ultimately became their new home.

Tour every space at our bio link. Photo by @aaronleitz; design by @brian.paquette_; words by Jennifer Flowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 05, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
When Leah Lippmann, an architect and senior interior designer at @knickerbockergroup, began renovating a waterfront home overlooking Maine’s Casco Bay, she had the mansions of Bar Harbor in mind. “They built these beautiful Shingle-style houses on the water,” she says. “They were in railroad, coal, magnates of some sort. They had a lot of money and that’s where they spent it.”

See the home she designed at our bio link. Photo by @darrensetlow; design by @knickerbockergroup; words by @robertbythebook.

node.text:
"As soon as we walked in, we knew this was the one,” says the French fashion designer @pierrehardy, wistfully recalling the moment he and husband @christopherturnier (CEO of Hardy’s eponymous brand) set foot inside the Seine-gazing 17th-century hôtel particulier on Île Saint-Louis, a small island smack in the middle of Paris that they now call home. They didn’t expect to fall for a place so quickly. But even totally empty and, by all accounts, a bit of a mess, the approximately 2,000-square-foot apartment was bursting with life.

Explore their elegant apartment at our bio link. Photo by @francoishalard; design by @vdecotiis; words by @_h_mart_.

The algorithm doesn’t lie. Slowly but surely, the Explore grid on @evachen212’s Instagram feed morphed from shoes, bags, and beauty serums into ceramics, mirrors, and house tours. Meanwhile, words like patina and names like Paul McCobb began to pepper her conversations and thoughts. All signs pointed to her latest project: the reno-vation of a Connecticut country home for her young family.

Step into her home from our latest issue at our bio link. Photo by @chrismottalini; produced by @janekeltnerdev; styled by @kellemiles; design by @hendrickschurchill; words by @samuelcochran.

The Big Apple was starting to bring celebrity chef turned interior designer @travislondon down. “I get so seasonally depressed in New York,” he says. “I knew I wanted to be in Miami.” The Florida hot spot’s neon-tinted exuberance was much more on London’s wavelength, so he decamped to the famously sunny city in early 2020 in search of a fresh start.

Tour his bold, colorful home at our bio link. Photo by @kris_tamburello; styled by Filip Berdek; design by @travislondon; words by @allie_weiss.
